- Thu 21 Feb 2019. Vuhovi : More Ebola in DRC as nurse's murder halts efforts
[CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy), abridged, edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/02/more-ebola-drc-nurses-murder-halts-efforts-vuhovi
[Byline: Stephanie Soucheray]

The Ministry of Health detailed the temporary halting of surveillance activities in Vuhovi after a nurse from the Bisongo health center was abducted and murdered. Officials said a group of unidentified people carried out the attack.

"Contrary to certain information that has circulated, the patients of the Vuhovi General Reference Hospital have not been [removed], and they continue to be cared for on site," the health ministry said, adding that it is encouraging health workers to resume outbreak activities.

New vaccination campaign
---------------------------
Today [21 Feb 2019] front-line workers in the Lolwa health zone, which lies between Komanda and Rwampara on the road connecting Beni to Bunia, were vaccinated in a preventive effort, the ministry said.

Also today [21 Feb 2019], the World Health Organization (WHO) published an outbreak update and noted that Katwa and Butembo remain areas of concern.

From 30 Jan to 19 Feb 2019, a total of 40 health areas in 12 health zones recorded 79 cases: Katwa (46), Butembo (15), Kyondo (4), Vuhovi (4), Kalunguta (2), Oicha (2), Biena (1), Mabalako (1), Manguredjipa (1), Masereka (1), Mutwanga (1), and Rwampara (1).

Survival trend for favipiravir recipients
--------------------------------------
In research news, today [21 Feb 2019] the Journal of Infectious Diseases published a retrospective study on survival rates of Ebola patients who received favipiravir in Guinea during the West African Ebola outbreak in 2015. Favipiravir, also known as T-705 or Avigan, is an experimental antiviral drug manufactured by Toyama Chemical of Japan.

In the study, the case fatality rate in favipiravir-treated patients was lower than in untreated patients (31 of 73 [42.5%] vs 52 of 90 [57.8%], P = 0.053 in univariate analysis), but the effect did not reach statistical significance.

Citation. Kerber R, Lorenz E, Duraffour S, et al. Laboratory findings, compassionate use of favipiravir, and outcome in patients with Ebola virus disease, Guinea, 2015 -- a retrospective observational study.
J Infect Dis 2019 https://doi.org/10.1093/infdis/jiz078.

